\subsubsection*{From the local to the global rate of change}

Define the \emph{finite–time, coarse–grain information content}
\[
\mathcal I_f(t,\tau)
\;=\;
\int_{\mathbb R^{n}}
I_f(x,t,\tau)\,
\underbrace{e^{t\mathcal L_f}\mu(dx)}_{=\mu_t(dx)} ,
\qquad 
I_f(x,t,\tau)=n+2\log\frac{e^{\tau\Delta}\mu_t}{\mu_t}.
\]
Because the Liouville operator is the generator of the push‑forward flow, the ordinary derivative of $\mathcal I_f$ can be written with the \emph{material} derivative $D_t=\partial_t+f\!\cdot\!\nabla$ computed in the previous subsection:
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\mathcal I_f(t,\tau)
\;=\;
\int D_t I_f(x,t,\tau)\,\mu_t(dx).
\tag{25}
\]

\paragraph{Selecting the physically meaningful path \boldmath$\,\tau(t)$}  
Exactly as for the local quantity, only the exponentially contracting path
\[
\tau(t)=\tau_0\,e^{-2\lambda t}, 
\qquad 
\lambda=\max\{\Re\!\operatorname{spec}\nabla f\},
\tag{26}
\]
keeps the right‑hand side of (25) finite in the double limit $t\!\to\!\infty$, $\tau\!\to\!0$.  
Along this path the term of highest asymptotic order in (25) is obtained by substituting the result
\[
D_t I_f(x,t,\tau)
\,=\,
-2\tau\,\bigl(s\!\otimes\! s\bigr)\!:\!\dot g_E
\;+\;\mathcal O(\tau e^{\lambda t}),
\qquad 
s=\nabla\log(e^{\tau\Delta}\mu_t),
\tag{27}
\]
where $\dot g_E=(\nabla f+\nabla f^{\!\top})$ is the Eulerian rate‑of‑strain tensor (the time derivative of the Euclidean metric pulled back by the flow).

\paragraph{Rate of change of the \emph{global} information dimension}

Using (26) in (25)–(27) and taking $t\!\to\!\infty$ we obtain
\[
\boxed{\;
\frac{d}{dt}D_I[\mu_t]
=\;
-2\tau_0\,e^{-2\lambda t}
\int_{\mathbb R^{n}}
\bigl(s\!\otimes\! s\bigr)\!:\!\dot g_E\;\mu_t(dx)\; }.
\tag{28}
\]

\subsubsection*{The tensor \boldmath$s\!\otimes\! s$ as the Fisher information metric}

For any smooth density $\rho$ on $\mathbb R^{n}$ the (translation) Fisher information matrix is
\[
\mathcal J[\rho]
\;=\;
\int_{\mathbb R^{n}}
\bigl(\nabla\log\rho\bigr)\!
\bigl(\nabla\log\rho\bigr)^{\!\top}\,
\rho(dx)
\;=\;
\int s\!\otimes\! s\;\rho(dx).
\tag{29}
\]
Hence $s\!\otimes\! s$ is \emph{point‑wise} the Riemannian metric whose expectation gives the Fisher information.  
Writing $S(t)=\tfrac12(\nabla f+\nabla f^{\!\top})$ for the symmetric part of the Jacobian, (28) becomes
\[
\frac{d}{dt}D_I[\mu_t]
=
-4\tau_0\,e^{-2\lambda t}\,
\operatorname{Tr}\!\bigl(\mathcal J[e^{\tau(t)\Delta}\mu_t]\,S(t)\bigr).
\tag{30}
\]
Equation (30) reveals the geometric mechanism behind dimension loss:

* $\,\mathcal J[e^{\tau(t)\Delta}\mu_t]$ is the Fisher (information‑geometric) metric of the \emph{coarse‑grained} measure;
* $\,S(t)$ is the infinitesimal stretching/compression imposed by the flow;
* their inner product $\operatorname{Tr}(\mathcal J\,S)$ quantifies how much the flow’s \emph{stable} eigendirections (negative part of $S$) align with the principal directions in which the measure carries Fisher information.

Because the prefactor $\tau_0 e^{-2\lambda t}$ decays exactly as the unstable directions expand, (30) stays finite and negative, giving a well‑defined \emph{rate at which the global information dimension decreases} as the measure concentrates onto its attractor.

\medskip
\noindent\textbf{Interpretation.}  
The contraction of the Fisher metric with the rate‑of‑strain tensor is reminiscent of the \emph{Shannon–Boltzmann H‑theorem}, but here the metric is not the Euclidean one: it is the data‑dependent Fisher metric that weights directions by the local signal‑to‑noise ratio of the probability measure.  Consequently, information (and hence dimension) is lost fastest along directions that are simultaneously (i) strongly contracting under $f$ and (ii) rich in Fisher information.  This formula therefore provides a quantitative bridge between dynamical stability theory and information geometry.
